    <node id="In Korvin's society, everyone is the governor. This means that there is no single ruler who forms policy or makes decisions, instead, the people themselves rule each other. This form of government is called democracy, where the power is in the hands of the people. There is no need for another ruler because the people have the power to make decisions and compel acceptance. However, it is important to note that this concept might be difficult for those from a different societal structure to understand, as demonstrated in the story." />
    <node id=". &quot;A paradox is not involved here; a government exists, and some being is the governor. Perhaps several beings share this task; perhaps machines do the work. But where there is a government, there is a governor. Is this agreed?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Certainly,&quot; Korvin said. &quot;It is completely obvious and true.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;The planet from which you come is part of a system of planets which are governed, you have said,&quot; the Ruler went on.&#10; &#10; &quot;True,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;Then there is a governor for this system,&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; &quot;True,&quot; Korvin said again.&#10; &#10; The ruler sighed gently. &quot;Explain this governor to us,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged. &quot;The explanation cannot be given to you.&quot;&#10; &#10; The Ruler turned to a group of his experts and a short muttered conversation took place. At its end the Ruler turned his gaze back to Korvin. &quot;Is the deficiency in you?&quot; he said. &quot;Are you in some way unable to describe this government?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;It can be described,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;Then you will suffer unpleasant consequences if you describe it to us?&quot; the" />
    <node id=", &quot;what is your government?&quot;&#10; &#10; The Ruler beckoned to a heavy-set green being, who stepped forward from a knot of Tr'en, inclined his head in Korvin's direction, and began. &quot;Our government is the only logical form of government,&quot; he said in a high, sweet tenor. &quot;The Ruler orders all, and his subjects obey. In this way uniformity is gained, and this uniformity aids in the speed of possible action and in the weight of action. All Tr'en act instantly in the same manner. The Ruler is adopted by the previous Ruler; in this way we are assured of a common wisdom and a steady judgment.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;You have heard our government defined,&quot; the Ruler said. &quot;Now, you will define yours for us.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin shook his head. &quot;If you insist,&quot; he said, &quot;I'll try it. But you won't understand it.&quot;&#10; &#10; The Ruler frowned. &quot;We shall understand,&quot; he said. &quot;Begin. Who governs you?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;None,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;But you are governed?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin nodded. &quot;Yes.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Then there is a governor,&quot; the Ruler" />
    <node id=".&#10; &#10; &quot;But you are governed?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin nodded. &quot;Yes.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Then there is a governor,&quot; the Ruler insisted.&#10; &#10; &quot;True,&quot; Korvin said. &quot;But everyone is the governor.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Then there is no government,&quot; the Ruler said. &quot;There is no single decision.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;No,&quot; Korvin said equably, &quot;there are many decisions binding on all.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Who makes them binding?&quot; the Ruler asked. &quot;Who forces you to accept these decisions? Some of them must be unfavorable to some beings?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Many of them are unfavorable,&quot; Korvin said. &quot;But we are not forced to accept them.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Do you act against your own interests?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged. &quot;Not knowingly,&quot; he said. The Ruler flashed a look at the technicians handling the lie-detector. Korvin turned to see their expression. They needed no words; the lie-detector was telling them, perfectly obviously, that he was speaking the truth. But the truth wasn't making any sense. &quot;I told you you wouldn't understand it,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; &quot;It is a defect in your explanation,&quot;" />
    <node id=" he said.&#10; &#10; A short silence was broken by one of the attendant experts. &quot;We have theorized that an underling may be permitted to make some of his own decisions, leaving only the more extensive ones for the master. This seems to us inefficient and liable to error, yet it is a possible system. Is it the system you mean?&quot;&#10; &#10; Very sharp, Korvin told himself grimly. &quot;It is,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; &quot;Then the government which reigns over several planets is supreme,&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; &quot;It is,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;Who is it that governs?&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; The key question had, at last, been asked. Korvin felt grateful that the logical Tr'en had determined to begin from the beginning, instead of going off after details of armament first; it saved a lot of time.&#10; &#10; &quot;The answer to that question,&quot; Korvin said, &quot;cannot be given to you.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Any question of fact has an answer,&quot; the Ruler snapped. &quot;A paradox is not involved here; a government exists, and some being is the governor. Perhaps several beings share this task; perhaps machines do the work" />
    <node id=" truth wasn't making any sense. &quot;I told you you wouldn't understand it,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; &quot;It is a defect in your explanation,&quot; the Ruler almost snarled.&#10; &#10; &quot;My explanation is as exact as it can be,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; The Ruler breathed gustily. &quot;Let us try something else,&quot; he said.&#10;&quot;Everyone is the governor. Do you share a single mind? A racial mind has been theorized, though we have met with no examples—&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Neither have we,&quot; Korvin said. &quot;We are all individuals, like yourselves.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;But with no single ruler to form policy, to make decisions—&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;We have no need of one,&quot; Korvin said calmly.&#10; &#10; &quot;Ah,&quot; the Ruler said suddenly, as if he saw daylight ahead. &quot;And why not?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;We call our form of government democracy ,&quot; Korvin said. &quot;It means the rule of the people. There is no need for another ruler.&quot;&#10; &#10; One of the experts piped up suddenly. &quot;The beings themselves rule each other?&quot; he said. &quot;This is clearly impossible; for, no one being can have the force to compel acceptance" />
    <node id="The Tr'en people, being a logical race, approach the paradoxes presented by Korvin during the lie-detector test with great interest and confusion. They initially believe that Korvin is attempting to confuse them or is a traitor to his planet, as his answers do not fit into their logical framework. However, they are also intrigued by the fact that Korvin's answers are truthful, which leads them to question their own understanding of logic and reality. The Tr'en become slightly puzzled and less confident when faced with unconventional behavior or answers, which ultimately allows for Korvin's successful escape. Their political structure is rigid, with a strong emphasis on logic and clarity, making it difficult for them to comprehend or respond effectively to situations that do not fit into their predefined categories." />
    <node id=" the other lovely paradox-models scattered around were so much primer material for the Tr'en. &quot;They can be treated mathematically,&quot; one of the experts, a small emerald-green being, told Korvin thinly. &quot;Of course, you would not understand the mathematics. But that is not important. You need only understand that we cannot be confused by such means.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Good,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; The experts blinked. &quot;Good?&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; &quot;Naturally,&quot; Korvin said in a friendly tone.&#10; &#10; The expert frowned horribly, showing all of his teeth. Korvin did his best not to react. &quot;Your plan is a failure,&quot; the expert said, &quot;and you call this a good thing. You can mean only that your plan is different from the one we are occupied with.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;True,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; There was a short silence. The expert beamed. He examined the indicators of the lie-detector with great care. &quot;What is your plan?&quot; he said at last, in a conspiratorial whisper.&#10; &#10; &quot;To answer your questions, truthfully and logically,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; The silence this time was even longer." />
    <node id="According to the description provided by the captive Korvin in front of the Tr’en Ruler, human males can vary greatly in height. Some men are over eight feet tall, while others are under four feet. Additionally, there is a group of humans who are never more than a foot and a half in height, and usually less than that - approximately nine or ten inches. This group is referred to as children." />
    <node id=" question. &quot;Some men are larger than I am,&quot; he said, &quot;and some are smaller.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Within what limits?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged. &quot;Some are over eight feet tall,&quot; he said, &quot;and others under four feet.&quot; He used the Tr'en measurement scale, of course; it didn't seem necessary, though, to mention that both extremes of height were at the circus-freak level. &quot;Then there is a group of humans,&quot; he went on, &quot;who are never more than a foot and a half in height, and usually less than that—approximately nine or ten inches. We call these children ,&quot; he volunteered helpfully.&#10; &#10; &quot;Approximately?&quot; the Ruler growled. &quot;We ask for precision here,&quot; he said. &quot;We are scientific men. We are exact.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin nodded hurriedly. &quot;Our race is more ... more approximate,&quot; he said apologetically.&#10; &#10; &quot;Slipshod,&quot; the Ruler muttered.&#10; &#10; &quot;Undoubtedly,&quot; Korvin agreed politely. &quot;I'll try to do the best I can for you.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;You will answer my questions,&quot; the Ruler said, &quot;with exactitude.&quot; He paused, frowning slightly" />
    <node id="Korvin's successful escape can be attributed to the lack of insight and confusion among the Tr'en, who follow a rigid logical framework in their society. When faced with unconventional answers during a lie-detector test, the Tr'en became puzzled, which allowed Korvin to slip away due to their subconscious inability to grasp unconventional behavior. This lack of insight also extended to security matters, as an unlocked door and a nearby weapon facilitated his escape.&#10;&#10;To send a message to Earth Central, Korvin utilized the psionic talents of the men there, despite not having such abilities himself. The Tr'en were unaware of this, demonstrating their lack of understanding regarding potential threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension. After his escape, Korvin sent a message declaring &quot;mission accomplished&quot; and provided food for thought to the Tr'en. This message contained indigestible ideas that would challenge the Tr'en's logical framework and potentially lead them towards democratic values and understanding of laws, which is not compatible with their current political structure." />
    <node id="The Tr'en are present because their Ruler wants to gain information from Korvin, who is being held captive. They are not necessarily interested in &quot;nothing&quot; with Korvin; rather, Didyak's statement of &quot;I have been ordered to come to you&quot; implies that the Tr'en are there specifically for the purpose of interacting with Korvin as part of their interrogation process. However, it is important to note that the Tr'en have a literalist approach to communication and may not always interpret or express ideas in the same way humans do, leading to potential misunderstandings." />
    <node id=",&quot; Didyak said, leaning against the door-frame. &quot;You have other questions?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin sighed. &quot;What are you doing here, then?&quot; he asked. As conversation, it wasn't very choice; but it was, he admitted, better than solitude.&#10; &#10; &quot;I am leaning against the door,&quot; Didyak said. The Tr'en literalist approach to the smallest problems of everyday living was a little hard to get the hang of, Korvin told himself bitterly. He thought for a second.&#10; &#10; &quot;Why did you come to me?&quot; he said at last.&#10; &#10; Didyak beamed at him. The sight was remarkably unpleasant, involving as it did the disclosure of the Tr'en fifty-eight teeth, mostly pointed. Korvin stared back impassively. &quot;I have been ordered to come to you,&quot; Didyak said, &quot;by the Ruler. The Ruler wishes to talk with you.&quot;&#10; &#10; It wasn't quite &quot;talk&quot;; that was a general word in the Tr'en language, and Didyak had used a specific meaning, roughly: &quot;gain information from, by peaceful and vocal means.&quot; Korvin filed it away for future reference. &quot;Why did the" />
    <node id="The purpose of Korvin's meeting with the Ruler in the Room of the Ruler is for Korvin to provide information about Earth, its government, weapons, plans, and fortifications. The Tr'en want this information so they can understand how decisions are made on Earth and whether underlings like Korvin face consequences for sharing sensitive information.&#10;&#10;Korvin agreed to answer the Ruler's questions after obtaining permission to ask a question himself, which was to inquire about the Tr'en government. The Ruler described their system as one where the previous Ruler adopts the new Ruler, ensuring common wisdom and steady judgment. Korvin then explained that his planet has no single governor, but is governed nonetheless, without specifying the details of Earth's government initially.&#10;&#10;The main goal for Korvin now is to provide enough information to satisfy the Tr'en curiosity while avoiding any revelations that could be harmful to Earth or other planets in their governing system." />
    <node id=" had used a specific meaning, roughly: &quot;gain information from, by peaceful and vocal means.&quot; Korvin filed it away for future reference. &quot;Why did the Ruler not come to me?&quot; Korvin asked.&#10; &#10; &quot;The Ruler is the Ruler,&quot; Didyak said, slightly discomfited. &quot;You are to go to him. Such is his command.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged, sighed and smoothed back his hair. &quot;I obey the command of the Ruler,&quot; he said—another ritual. Everybody obeyed the command of the Ruler. If you didn't, you never had a second chance to try.&#10; &#10; But Korvin meant exactly what he'd said. He was going to obey the commands of the Ruler of the Tr'en—and remove the Tr'en threat from the rest of the galaxy forever.&#10; &#10; That, after all, was his job.&#10; &#10; &#10; &#10; The Room of the Ruler was large, square and excessively brown. The walls were dark-brown, the furnishings—a single great chair, several kneeling-benches and a small table near the chair—were light-brown, of some metallic substance, and even the drapes were tan. It was," />
    <node id=" he announced, &quot;has been adjusted satisfactorily to your physiology. The questioning will now continue.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin swallowed again. The test hadn't really seemed extensive enough to him. But, after all, the Tr'en knew their business, better than anyone else could know it. They had the technique and the logic and the training.&#10; &#10; He hoped they were right.&#10; &#10; The Ruler was frowning at him. Korvin did his best to look receptive.&#10;&quot;Why did you land your ship on this planet?&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; &quot;My job required it,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; The Ruler nodded. &quot;Your job is to crash your ship,&quot; he said. &quot;It is wasteful but the machines tell me it is true. Very well, then; we shall find out more about your job. Was the crash intentional?&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin looked sober. &quot;Yes,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; The Ruler blinked. &quot;Very well,&quot; he said. &quot;Was your job ended when the ship crashed?&quot; The Tr'en word, of course, wasn't ended , nor did it mean exactly that. As nearly as Korvin could make out, it meant&#10;&quot;disposed of for all" />
    <node id="The Tr'en term 'disposed of for all time' signifies the permanent elimination or removal of something, according to the Ruler. Korvin's response of 'Staying alive' is considered insufficient or untruthful in the Ruler's perspective because it does not directly address the concept of a job being ended or completed in a way that the Tr'en can understand. The Tr'en have a logical and systematic approach to government and problem-solving, and they likely view a job as having a clear beginning, middle, and end. By saying that his job is to 'stay alive', Korvin challenges this perspective by implying that his job is ongoing and not easily defined, which the Ruler and other Tr'en find confusing and difficult to accept." />
    <node id=" of course, wasn't ended , nor did it mean exactly that. As nearly as Korvin could make out, it meant&#10;&quot;disposed of for all time.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;No,&quot; he said.&#10; &#10; &quot;What else does your job entail?&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; Korvin decided to throw his first spoke into the wheel. &quot;Staying alive.&quot;&#10; &#10; The Ruler roared. &quot;Do not waste time with the obvious!&quot; he shouted.&#10;&quot;Do not try to trick us; we are a logical and scientific race! Answer correctly.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;I have told the truth,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;But it is not—not the truth we want,&quot; the Ruler said.&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged. &quot;I replied to your question,&quot; he said. &quot;I did not know that there was more than one kind of truth. Surely the truth is the truth, just as the Ruler is the Ruler?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;I—&quot; The Ruler stopped himself in mid-roar. &quot;You try to confuse the Ruler,&quot; he said at last, in an approximation of his usual one. &quot;But the Ruler will not be confused. We have experts in matters of logic&quot;—the Tr'en word" />
    <node id="In a system where everyone is the governor and there is no single decision-maker, binding decisions are made through the democratic process. The people themselves make decisions that are then binding on all members of society. This process does not rely on force or coercion, but rather on the collective agreement and consensus of the governed. In this type of system, decisions may not always be favorable to everyone, but individuals are not forced to accept them against their will. Instead, they participate in the decision-making process and agree to abide by the outcomes, even if some decisions may be unfavorable to certain groups or individuals. This system relies on mutual respect, trust, and a commitment to upholding the collective good." />
    <node id="The system of governance on Earth is called democracy, where the people themselves are the governors. This means that there is no single ruler who forms policy or makes decisions; instead, the power is in the hands of the people. Decisions regarding weapons, plans, and fortifications on Earth are made through a democratic process, where the people participate in decision-making and agree to abide by the outcomes. Binding decisions are made through this collective agreement and consensus, rather than through force or coercion.&#10;&#10;At the same time, Earth is also part of a larger government that governs several planets. However, the details of this larger government and the identity of who governs it cannot be disclosed, as per Korvin's statements in the story. This information is withheld to prevent any harm to Earth or other planets in the governing system." />
    <node id="The Tr'en's anticipated membership in the Comity of Planets required not only advanced technological abilities but also linguistic and cultural understanding. This is because efficient communication, empathy, and the ability to comprehend diverse perspectives are crucial for successful interaction among different civilizations. The Tr'en, being an efficiently logical race, initially struggled to understand unconventional behavior and answers provided by Korvin during a lie-detector test.&#10;&#10;Their rigid political structure, with a strong emphasis on logic and clarity, made it difficult for them to comprehend or respond effectively to situations that did not fit into their predefined categories. This lack of understanding was further demonstrated when Korvin utilized the psionic talents of the men at Earth Central to send a message, revealing their potential ignorance of threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension.&#10;&#10;For the Tr'en to be successful members of the Comity of Planets, they would need to develop a greater appreciation for linguistic and cultural nuances to avoid misunderstandings and respond effectively to various situations. This would allow them to interact more successfully with a diverse range of civilizations and help maintain peace and cooperation within the interstellar community." />
    <node id="LOST IN TRANSLATION&#10; &#10;&#10; By&#10; &#10;&#10; LARRY M. HARRIS&#10; &#10; In language translation, you may get a literally accurate word-for-word translation ... but miss the meaning entirely. And in space-type translation ... the effect may be the same!&#10; &#10;&#10; Illustrated by Schoenherr&#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; The cell had been put together more efficiently than any Korvin had ever been in. But that was only natural, he told himself sadly; the Tr'en were an efficient people. All the preliminary reports had agreed on that; their efficiency, as a matter of fact, was what had made Korvin's arrival a necessity. They were well into the atomic era, and were on the verge of developing space travel. Before long they'd be settling the other planets of their system, and then the nearer stars. Faster-than-light travel couldn't be far away, for the magnificently efficient physical scientists of the Tr'en—and that would mean, in the ordinary course of events, an invitation to join the Comity of Planets.&#10; &#10; An invitation, the Comity was sure, which the Tr'en would not accept.&#10; &#10; Korvin stretched out on the" />
    <node id="In this story, Korvin is allowed to ask a question about the nature of the Tr'en government before he provides information about Earth and its governing system. The Tr'en have a hierarchical government where the previous Ruler adopts the new Ruler, ensuring common wisdom and steady judgment.&#10;&#10;When answering the Ruler's questions about Earth's government, Korvin initially avoids giving specific details and states that his planet has no single governor, but is governed nonetheless. Later on, he reveals that Earth is governed by a system where both individual decisions and collective decisions are made, implying a complex governing body involving multiple entities and levels of authority.&#10;&#10;Korvin ultimately decides to reveal that the answer to who governs Earth cannot be given to the Tr'en, emphasizing that the nature of Earth's government is not something he can disclose. This suggests that the ruling system on Earth may be too complex or different from the Tr'en's hierarchical system for them to fully understand, or that there are security reasons for withholding this information." />
    <node id="The Tr'en term 'disposed of for all time' is understood by Korvin to mean the permanent elimination or removal of something. This term signifies a completed job or task in the perspective of the Tr'en, who have a logical and systematic approach to government and problem-solving, viewing jobs as having clear beginnings, middles, and ends.&#10;&#10;The Ruler believes that there is more than one kind of truth because Korvin's initial response of 'Staying alive' when asked about his job does not directly address the concept of a job being ended or completed in a way the Tr'en can understand. By implying that his job is ongoing and not easily defined, Korvin challenges the Tr'en perspective, causing confusion and difficulty for the Ruler and other Tr'en to accept." />
    <node id="The purpose of Korvin's meeting with the Ruler in the Room of the Ruler is for him to provide information about Earth's government, weapons, plans, and fortifications. The Tr'en want this information to understand how decisions are made on Earth and whether underlings like Korvin face consequences for sharing sensitive information." />
    <node id="Korvin initially avoids giving detailed information about Earth's governing system because he wants to understand the nature of the Tr'en government first. Later on, he reveals that Earth is governed by a system where both individual and collective decisions are made, implying a complex governing body involving multiple entities and levels of authority.&#10;&#10;However, Korvin ultimately decides not to disclose specific details about Earth's government when asked by the Ruler, stating that it cannot be explained to the Tr'en. While the story does not provide a clear reason for this decision, it can be inferred that either the nature of Earth's governing system is too complex or different from the Tr'en's hierarchical system for them to fully understand, or there are security reasons for withholding this information.&#10;&#10;As for what would happen if Korvin were to describe Earth's government to the Tr'en, he suggests that there would be &quot;unpleasant consequences,&quot; but does not elaborate further. This statement could be interpreted as a warning of potential danger or negative outcomes if such sensitive information were to be disclosed to an unfamiliar and potentially hostile entity." />
    <node id="The purpose of the truth testing machine being attached to Korvin, according to the Ruler, is to determine if he is lying or not. It is a lie-detector that has been adjusted to Korvin's physiology and will be used to verify the accuracy of his responses during the interrogation by the Ruler." />
    <node id=" the best I can for you.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;You will answer my questions,&quot; the Ruler said, &quot;with exactitude.&quot; He paused, frowning slightly. &quot;You landed your ship on this planet,&quot; he went on. &quot;Why?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;My job required it,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;A clumsy lie,&quot; the Ruler said. &quot;The ship crashed; our examinations prove that beyond any doubt.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;True,&quot; Korvin said.&#10; &#10; &quot;And it is your job to crash your ship?&quot; the Ruler said. &quot;Wasteful.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin shrugged again. &quot;What I say is true,&quot; he announced. &quot;Do you have tests for such matters?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;We do,&quot; the Ruler told him. &quot;We are an exact and a scientific race. A machine for the testing of truth has been adjusted to your physiology. It will be attached to you.&quot;&#10; &#10; Korvin looked around and saw it coming through the door, pushed by two technicians. It was large and squat and metallic, and it had wheels, dials, blinking lights, tubes and wires, and a seat with armrests and straps. It was obviously a form of lie-detector—and Kor" />
    <node id="Based on the text provided, when the Ruler asked &quot;what is your government?&quot;, Korvin responded by saying &quot;none&quot; governs them. However, he clarified that they are still governed, but not by a single governor or ruling entity. Instead, everyone on his planet serves as the governor, with many decisions being made collectively and binding on all members of the society. The concept is difficult for the Ruler to understand because it's different from their centralized system where one ruler makes all decisions and others obey without question.&#10;&#10;Korvin also mentions that his planet operates under a collective form of government, where many decisions are made by the collective population and binding on all members. He emphasizes that no single entity forces them to accept unfavorable decisions, yet they generally don't act against their own interests knowingly. This type of governance is in stark contrast with the Ruler's system, leading to confusion among the Tr'en officials as they struggle to comprehend how a society can function effectively without a centralized decision-maker.&#10;&#10;It's also worth noting that when the Ruler asks if Earth is part of a larger government or exists alone, Korvin responds by saying &quot;both,&quot; implying some sort of multi-level governance structure where their planet is both an individual entity and part of a broader collective." />
    <node id="Based on the story, the specific identity or nature of who or what governs the government that reigns over several planets cannot be disclosed. When the Ruler asked Korvin &quot;Who is it that governs?&quot; Korvin responded by saying &quot;The answer to that question cannot be given to you.&quot; This was met with no further pressing from the Tr'en, suggesting that there may be security reasons for withholding this information or that the nature of Earth's government is too complex or different from the Tr'en's hierarchical system for them to fully understand. Therefore, it remains unknown who or what governs the government that reigns over several planets." />
    <node id="The purpose of the truth-testing machine being attached to Korvin, according to the Ruler, is to verify the accuracy of his responses during the interrogation. This lie-detector has been adjusted to Korvin's physiology to determine if he is lying or telling the truth. The Ruler's race values exactitude and logic, using this machine to ensure they are getting correct information from Korvin." />
    <node id="The purpose of testing the machine on Korvin is to verify the accuracy of his responses during the interrogation by the Ruler. This truth-detecting machine has been adjusted to Korvin's physiology to determine if he is lying or telling the truth. The process involves attaching the machine to Korvin and asking him questions while monitoring the machine's readings.&#10;&#10;The machine reveals his ability to tell a lie by measuring Korvin's physiological responses, such as heart rate, blood pressure, and sweat production, which can change when a person is lying. The machine interprets these changes and indicates whether or not Korvin is telling the truth. For example, if Korvin lies about crashing his ship intentionally, the machine would likely detect discrepancies in his physiological responses and indicate that he is lying. However, it's important to note that no lie-detector is 100% accurate and can be influenced by factors such as stress, illness, or fear." />
    <node id="1. The reason for Korvin's intense boredom while being held captive alone on Tr'en is that there are no other prisoners or guards with whom he can interact, and he has already exhausted the concentrated language lessons given by the guards each night due to his unconsciousness. He is left alone with smooth walls, food concentrates, and no distractions.&#10;&#10;2. The one who has arrived at Korvin's cell door as he contemplates telling anything to anyone just for the chance at conversation is Didyak of the Tr'en. According to the story, Didyak was sent by the Ruler to bring Korvin for an interrogation session with the truth-testing machine attached to him to verify the accuracy of his responses during the questioning." />
    <node id=" of tourist pictures. The Wonders of Tr'en, according to all the advance reports, were likely to be pretty boring, but they'd have been better than nothing.&#10; &#10; In any decently-run jail, he told himself with indignation, there would at least have been other prisoners to talk to. But on Tr'en Korvin was all alone.&#10; &#10; True, every night the guards came in and gave him a concentrated lesson in the local language, but Korvin failed to get much pleasure out of that, being unconscious at the time. But now he was equipped to discuss almost anything from philosophy to plumbing, but there was nobody to discuss it with. He changed position on the bunk and stared at the walls. The Tr'en were efficient; there weren't even any imperfections in the smooth surface to distract him.&#10; &#10; He wasn't tired and he wasn't hungry; his captors had left him with a full stock of food concentrates.&#10; &#10; But he was almightily bored, and about ready to tell anything to anyone, just for the chance at a little conversation.&#10; &#10; As he reached this dismal conclusion, the cell door opened. Korvin got up off the bunk in a hurry and spun around" />
    <node id="Based on the story, the Tr'en have a hierarchical government where the previous Ruler adopts the new Ruler. This is revealed when Korvin asks about the nature of the Tr'en government before providing information about Earth's governing system. The Ruler describes their system as one where common wisdom and steady judgment are ensured through this adoption process.&#10;&#10;However, the story does not provide further details about the structure or specific workings of the Tr'en government beyond this hierarchical relationship between the previous and new Rulers." />
    <node id="The main reason for Korvin's escape plan was his understanding of the rigid logical framework and lack of insight among the Tr'en. This allowed him to take advantage of their subconscious inability to grasp unconventional behavior, which facilitated his escape through an unlocked door and the presence of a nearby weapon.&#10;&#10;Korvin managed to send a message to Earth Central by utilizing the psionic talents of the men there, despite not having such abilities himself. The Tr'en were unaware of this exploitation, demonstrating their lack of understanding regarding potential threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension. He sent the message declaring &quot;mission accomplished&quot; and providing food for thought to the Tr'en, which contained indigestible ideas challenging their logical framework and potentially leading them towards democratic values and understanding of laws." />
    <node id="Didyak of the Tr'en is the green, humanoid visitor who visits Korvin in his prison cell. Korvin hesitates from attempting to overpower Didyak because he realizes that it would be futile and potentially dangerous. At this point, Korvin does not know the full capabilities or intentions of the Tr'en, and attacking Didyak could lead to negative consequences for him. Furthermore, Didyak has come to take Korvin to the Ruler for an interrogation session, and Korvin is keen on gaining the opportunity to interact with someone from the Tr'en hierarchy in order to observe their communication style and learn more about their government and culture. All of these factors contribute to Korvin's decision not to attack Didyak in his prison cell." />
    <node id="In Korvin's society, the people themselves govern through a system called democracy. This means that there is no single ruler who forms policy or makes decisions; instead, the power is in the hands of the people. When Korvin initially states that &quot;none governs them,&quot; he might be emphasizing the lack of a single ruler or hierarchical authority figure like the Tr'en Ruler. However, when he clarifies that Earth is governed by both individual decisions and collective decisions made through multiple entities and levels of authority, it becomes clear that power rests with the people, who participate in decision-making and agree to abide by the outcomes.&#10;&#10;In summary, although Korvin's wording may be ambiguous, the system of governance on Earth is a democracy where the people are the governors. There is no single ruler or governing body, but rather a complex interplay between individual and collective decisions at multiple levels." />
    <node id="The reason given by Korvin for landing his ship on this planet is not explicitly stated in the provided text. However, it can be inferred that it may have been due to some sort of emergency or unforeseen circumstances, as he mentions that they &quot;had no choice&quot; but to land there. The Ruler's response to this explanation is not directly addressed either, but it is mentioned that the Tr'en are curious about Earth and its governance, which may have been a topic of discussion during their meeting. Additionally, the Ruler expresses interest in learning about Earth's weapons, plans, and fortifications, indicating a potential focus of their conversation." />
    <node id="1. The Tr'en's rigid logical framework and lack of insight: The Tr'en have a strictly logical society, which made them confused when confronted with unconventional answers during Korvin's lie-detector test. This confusion allowed Korvin to escape due to their subconscious inability to grasp unconventional behavior. Additionally, this lack of insight extended to security matters, as an unlocked door and a nearby weapon facilitated his escape.&#10;&#10;2. The Tr'en's limited understanding of threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension: After his escape, Korvin sent a message to Earth Central using the psionic talents of the men there, demonstrating that the Tr'en were unaware of potential threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension.&#10;&#10;3. The hierarchical nature of the Tr'en government: Before providing information about Earth's governing system, Korvin asked about the nature of the Tr'en government, revealing its hierarchical structure based on adoption by the previous Ruler to ensure common wisdom and steady judgment. This rigidity in their political structure contributed to the Tr'en's confusion and inability to respond effectively to unexpected situations like Korvin's escape.&#10;&#10;4. Korvin's decision not to attack Didyak: When faced with Didyak, the green, humanoid visitor who visited him in his prison cell, Korvin chose not to overpower him because he realized it would be futile and potentially dangerous. By not attacking Didyak, Korvin gained the opportunity to interact with someone from the Tr'en hierarchy, observe their communication style, and learn more about their government and culture.&#10;&#10;These factors together contributed to Korvin's successful escape and subsequent sending of a message to Earth Central. The rigidity and limitations in the Tr'en's political structure and lack of insight into threats or capabilities beyond their own comprehension facilitated Korvin's ability to exploit these weaknesses and successfully communicate with Earth Central, ultimately challenging the Tr'en's logical framework and potentially leading them towards democratic values and understanding of laws." />
    <node id="Based on the story, the purpose of crashing Korvin's ship on the Tr'en planet was part of his job requirements. The exact nature of his job or mission is not explicitly mentioned, but it seems that his task involved deliberately wrecking his spacecraft. In response to the Ruler's questioning, Korvin confirms that the crash was intentional and a necessary part of his duties.&#10;&#10;As for the outcome of crashing the ship on this planet and its impact on his status, there are no direct consequences mentioned in the story. It appears that the Tr'en people are more interested in learning about Earth's government, weapons, plans, and fortifications than punishing Korvin for his actions. While they initially suspect him of being a traitor or attempting to deceive them, their suspicions seem to be based on misunderstandings rather than any direct consequences resulting from the ship crash. Therefore, there is no significant change in Korvin's status as a result of crashing his ship on the Tr'en planet." />
    <node id="In a society where everyone is the governor and there is no single decision-maker, binding decisions are made through the democratic process. These decisions result from collective agreement and consensus among the governed, rather than relying on force or coercion. Individuals participate in the decision-making process and agree to abide by the outcomes, even if some decisions may be unfavorable to certain groups or individuals. This system relies on mutual respect, trust, and a commitment to upholding the collective good. The enforcement of these decisions is not done through physical force but rather through social norms, peer pressure, and the understanding that everyone has agreed to abide by the results of the democratic process." />
    <node id="Based on the story, the Tr’en Ruler has learned through the captive human Korvin that human males can vary greatly in height. Some men are over eight feet tall, while others are under four feet. There is also a group of humans who are never more than a foot and a half in height, usually less than that - approximately nine or ten inches. This group is referred to as children.&#10;&#10;However, the story does not provide further details about human physical characteristics beyond height. It can be assumed that humans have various other physical characteristics such as different skin colors, hair colors, eye colors, and body types, but this information is not explicitly stated in the provided text." />
